Note:
Linux ARM32 (EABI) System Call Definitions

Defines all system call numbers, platform metadata, and registration logic for
Linux running on ARM 32-bit processors using the EABI (Embedded Application
Binary Interface). ARM32 uses the traditional Linux syscall numbering with a
base offset of 0 for the EABI (the OABI used __NR_SYSCALL_BASE = 0x900000
but OABI is deprecated and not supported here).

ARM32 has both legacy syscalls (open, stat, etc.) and *at-suffixed variants
(openat, fstatat64, etc.) added in Linux 2.6.16+. We provide both since
the legacy calls are still widely used on 32-bit systems.

Syscall convention (EABI):
- Syscall number in R7
- Arguments in R0, R1, R2, R3, R4, R5
- Return value in R0
- Invoked via: swi 0 (software interrupt)

ARM32 uses 32-bit off_t by default. For 64-bit file offsets, use
the 64-bit variants (fstat64, lseek via _llseek, mmap2 instead of mmap).

Reference: Linux kernel arch/arm/tools/syscall.tbl
:End Note

Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/platforms/platform_interface.runa" as PlatformInterface
Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/syscall_registry.runa" as SyscallRegistry
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

